SIMPLE: interlocutory
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interlocutory
<hw>In`ter*loc"u*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LL.
<ets>interlocutorius</ets>, F. <ets>interlocutoire</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting of, or having the nature of, dialogue;
conversational.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Interlocutory</qex> discourses in the Holy Scriptures.</q>
<rj><qau>Fiddes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Intermediate; not final or
definitive; made or done during the progress of an action; <as>as, an
<ex>interlocutory</ex> judgement</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ An order, sentence, decree, or judgment, given in an
intermediate stage between the commencement and termination of a cause,
is called <xex>interlocutory</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interlocutory</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Interlocutory
<hw>In`ter*loc"u*to*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>interlocutoire</ets>.]</ety> <def>Interpolated discussion or
dialogue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interlocutrice</ent>⟦br⟧
